sentence: Broad-market exchange-traded funds, including SPY, IWM and IVV are all moving lower in pre-market trading .
Actively-traded PowerShares QQQ ( QQQ ) fell 0.25%.

U.S. stock futures are pointing to a lower open after a late selloff in Chinese stocks unsettled global markets, while weaker-than-expected results from retail giant Wal-Mart ( WMT ) dented sentiment at home.
The company's revenue beat expectations, but earnings per share missed the mark and it reduced its full-year guidance.

There was also a mixed bag of news from other retailers reporting Monday, with Home Depot ( HD ) and Dicks Sporting Goods ( DKS ) topping the Street view and clothing chain American Apparel ( APP ) warning that it doesn't have enough money to operate for the next 12 months.
In economic news, July housing starts and permits are out at 8:30 a.m.
ET Tuesday and are expected to show an increase in starts to 1.180 million from 1.174 million.
Permits are seen at 1.230 million from a revised 1.337 million in June.
Consumer Staples Select Sector SPDR (XLP) edged down, iShares Dow Jones US Consumer Goods (IYK), and Vanguard Consumer Staples ETF (VDC) were inactive after closing higher Monday.

Meanwhile, Consumer Discretionary Select Sector SPDR (XLY) was flat, SPDR S&P Retail (XRT) gained 0.5%, PowerShares Dynamic Retail (PMR) and Market Vectors Retail ETF (RTH) were firmer on Monday and unchanged so far pre-market.

Wal-Mart Stores ( WMT ) shares are down 3% after the world's biggest retailer reported Q2 2016 results that missed the Street view on earnings per share but beat estimates on total revenues as the company lowered full year guidance.

The company reported Q2 income from continuing operations of $3.48 billion, or $1.08 per share, down from $3.92 billion, or $1.21 per share, in the prior year period and missing analyst estimates of $1.12.
Currency exchange rates negatively impacted EPS by approximately $0.04.
Total revenues of $120.23 billion were up from $120.13 billion in Q2 2015 and topped analyst projections of $119.14 billion.
Comparable sales at Walmart U.S. increased 1.5%, driven by traffic of 1.3%.
Neighborhood Market comps increased approximately 7.3%, with strong growth from new stores, the company said.
Walmart updated full year EPS guidance to a range of $4.40 to $4.70 from a previous range of $4.70 to $5.05, below analyst estimates of $4.76.
The company guided Q3 EPS in a range of $0.93 to $1.05, missing analyst projections of $1.08.
Health Care SPDR (XLV) was edging lower, iShares Dow Jones US Healthcare (IYH) and Vanguard Health Care ETF (VHT) were flat after a higher close Monday.
Meanwhile, Biotech ETF iShares NASDAQ Biotechnology Index (IBB) slipped 0.17%.

Lannett Co (LCI), a generic pharmaceutical company, said its Silarx Pharmaceuticals subsidiary has received approval from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration to launch sales of the generic version of the antidepressant ABILIFY.
The approval comes in response to an Abbreviated New Drug Application (ANDA) for Aripiprazole Oral Solution 1 mg/mL.
LCI has begun shipments of the medication.
Annual total sales of Aripiprazole 1 mg/ml Oral Solution at Average Wholesale Price were approximately $76 million, according to IMS data cited by LCI.
Select Financial Sector SPDRs (XLF) fell 0.2% and Direxion Daily Financial Bull 3X shares (FAS) edging higher; Direxion Daily Financial Bear 3X Shares (FAZ) also higher, up 0.3%.

BB&T (BBT), a financial holding company, said late Monday that it has entered into a definitive agreement to acquire National Penn Bancshares, Inc. (NPBC) for approximately $1.8 billion in cash and stock.

Under the terms of the agreement, the total consideration for the merger will be approximately $1.8 billion consisting approximately $550 million in cash and approximately 31.6 million BB&T common shares, subject to certain adjustments.

Technology Select Sector SPDR ETF (XLK), iShares Dow Jones US Technology ETF (IYW), iShares S&P North American Technology ETF (IGM) were all inactive pre-market and iShares S&P North American Technology-Software Index (IGV) slipped 0.15%.
SPDR S&P International Technology Sector ETF (IPK) was inactive after a lower close.
Semiconductor ETFs, SPDR S&P Semiconductor (XSD) and Semiconductor Sector Index Fund (SOXX) were inactive after closing higher.

Social media site Twitter ( TWTR ) has appointed Singapore-based executive Rishi Jaitly as part of its plan to build content partnerships in Asia Pacific and the Middle East, Reuters reported Tuesday.

Reuters said Jaitly, who previously served as the market director of Twitter's India and Southeast Asia operations, will lead teams in Australia, India, and Japan while expanding into Greater China and Southeast Asia.
Dow Jones U.S. Energy Fund (IYE) was flat and Energy Select Sector SPDR (XLE) was leaning into the red.
West Texas Intermediate crude oil futures for delivery in September were trading at close to six and a half year lows, down by 0.2% to $41.67 per barrel; United States Oil Fund (USO) fell 0.6%.
Natural gas was down 0.8% and United States Natural Gas Fund (UNG) dropped 0.8%.
Gold was inching higher, and SPDR Gold Trust (GLD) was up 0.2%.
